<DOC><DOCNO>  ZF109-428-071  </DOCNO><DOCID>09 428 071.andM;</DOCID><JOURNAL>Newsbytes  August 2 1990* Full Text COPYRIGHT Newsbytes Inc. 1990.andM;</JOURNAL><TITLE>Canada Remote Systems - largest bbs - goes down. (electronicbulletin board service)</TITLE><AUTHOR>Woods, Wendy; Buckler, Grant.andM;</AUTHOR><DESCRIPT>Company:   Canada Remote Systems Ltd. (finance).andO;Topic:     Computer bulletin boardsInformation servicesBusinessFailureCanada.andM;</DESCRIPT><TEXT>CANADA REMOTE SYSTEMS - LARGEST BBS - GOES DOWN MISSISSAUGA, ONTARIO, CANADA,1990 AUG 2 (NB) -- Canada Remote Systems, the largest bulletin board inCanada, has suddenly gone out of business, an move which affects its 8,000subscribers.andP;  Although callers can still sign onto the system, they are beinginformed by an online notice that the system is closing, and a receiver willbe appointed to liquidate it.andM;Jud Newell, who, along with his wife, owns Canada Remote Systems, tellsNewsbytes that the company will not be taking any new memberships and theoffice is closed.andP;  He says the demise of the BBS was due to too rapidexpansion and not enough income.andM;&quot;For many many years we saw revenue increases of 30 to 50 percent.andP;  In 1989to 1990 we saw basically no increase in revenue, yet our plans in 1988 werepredicated on continuing growth.&quot; In 1989, he says, Canada Remote Systemsmoved out of its old premesis into a new building, and expanded from 54 to100 nodes, or incoming lines.andM;Newell attributes the lack of new members to the board in 1989 and 1990 tothe economy.andP;  &quot;The entire market in Canada is deadly,&quot; he said.andP;  &quot;We're in arecession right now.&quot;andM;He said Canada Remote Systems' major creditor is Bell Canada.andM;Newell says there is a grassroots movement starting among members of theboard who wish to keep it alive.andP;  &quot;We have indications from a number ofmembers that they will purchase the assets of the bulletin board side whichwill allow it to continue,&quot; he said.andP;  A meeting has been scheduled forSaturday at the company's office, 1331 Crestlawn Drive, Unit D, Mississauga,Ontario, Canada.andM;Canada Remote Systems, established in 1981, has access both through localphone numbers in Canada and through Inet, the Bell Canada gateway service.andO;The system's original name was Toronto RCP/M (Remote CP/M) Systems.andM;The system offered a wide range of public-domain software and shareware,information services, and a message system with connections to many otherbulletin board systems.andM;There were signs of trouble just recently when Canada Remote sent out aletter announcing a fee increase and urging early membership renewals.andP;  &quot;Asthe economy boomed, so did CRS,&quot; the letter said.andP;  &quot;However, the economyisn't booming any more, and we've noticed dramatic changes in ouroperations.&quot;andP;  CRS laid off several staff members in May.andM;Subscribers paid an annual fee averaging $80 and were allowed up to two hoursonline each day.andM;(Wendy Woods andamp; Grant Buckler/19900802)</TEXT></DOC>